[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] The central feature of **Hoare logic** is the **Hoare triple**.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] A triple describes how the execution of a piece of code changes the state of the computation.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] where P and Q are *assertions* and C is a *command*.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] P is named the *precondition* and Q the *postcondition*: when the precondition is met, executing the command establishes the postcondition.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Assertions are formulae in predicate logic.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Hoare logic provides axioms and inference rules for all the constructs of a simple imperative programming language.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] In addition to the rules for the simple language in Hoare's original paper, rules for other language constructs have been developed since then by Hoare and many other researchers.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] There are rules for concurrency, procedures, jumps, and pointers.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Using standard Hoare logic, only partial correctness can be proven.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Total correctness additionally requires termination, which can be proven separately or with an extended version of the While rule.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Thus, the intuitive reading of a Hoare triple is: Whenever P holds of the state before the execution of C , then Q will hold afterwards, or C does not terminate.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] In the latter case, there is no "after", so Q can be any statement at all.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Indeed, one can choose Q to be false to express that C does not terminate.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] The empty statement rule asserts that the skip statement does not change the state of the program, thus whatever holds true before skip also holds true afterwards.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom states that, after the assignment, any predicate that was previously true for the right-hand side of the assignment now holds for the variable.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Formally, let P be an assertion in which the variable x is free.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] where $P[E/x]$ denotes the assertion P in which each free occurrence of x has been replaced by the expression E.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom scheme means that the truth of $P[E/x]$ is equivalent to the after-assignment truth of P.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Thus, were $P[E/x]$ true before the assignment, by the assignment axiom, then P would be true afterwards.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Conversely, were $P[E/x]$ false (i.e. $\neg P[E/x]$ true) prior to the assignment statement, P must then be false afterwards.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] All preconditions that are not modified by the expression can be carried over to the postcondition.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] In the first example, assigning $y:=x+1$ does not change the fact that $x+1=43$ , so both statements may appear in the postcondition.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Formally, this result is obtained by applying the axiom schema with P being ( $y=43$ and $x+1=43$ ), which yields $P[(x+1)/y]$ being ( $x+1=43$ and $x+1=43$ ), which can in turn be simplified to the given precondition $x+1=43$ .
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom scheme is equivalent to saying that to find the precondition, first take the post-condition and replace all occurrences of the left-hand side of the assignment with the right-hand side of the assignment.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] While a given postcondition P uniquely determines the precondition $P[E/x]$ , the converse is not true.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] are valid instances of the assignment axiom scheme.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] The assignment axiom proposed by Hoare *does not apply* when more than one name may refer to the same stored value.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] is wrong if x and y refer to the same variable (aliasing), although it is a proper instance of the assignment axiom scheme (with both $\{P\}$ and $\{P[2/x]\}$ being $\{y=3\}$ ).
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Another example is shown in the right box.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] The conditional rule states that a postcondition Q common to then and else part is also a postcondition of the whole if...endif statement.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] In the then and the else part, the unnegated and negated condition B can be added to the precondition P, respectively.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] The condition, B, must not have side effects.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] An example is given in the next section.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] This rule was not contained in Hoare's original publication.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] the conditional rule can be derived from the other Hoare rules.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] In a similar way, rules for other derived program constructs, like for loop, do...until loop, switch, break, continue can be reduced by program transformation to the rules from Hoare's original paper.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] This rule permits strengthening the precondition $P_{2}$ and/or to weaken the postcondition $Q_{2}$ .
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] It is used, e.g., to achieve literally identical postconditions for the then and the else part.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] The consequence rule is needed to strengthen the precondition $\{-1\leq x<15\}$ obtained from the assignment rule to $\{0\leq x<15\}$ required for the conditional rule.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] hence the consequence rule has to be applied with $P_{1}$ and $P_{2}$ being $\{x=15\}$ and $\{{\texttt {true}}\}$ , respectively, to strengthen again the precondition.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Informally, the effect of the consequence rule is to "forget" that $\{x=15\}$ is known at the entry of the else part, since the assignment rule used for the else part doesn't need that information.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Here P is the loop invariant, which is to be preserved by the loop body S.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] After the loop is finished, this invariant P still holds, and moreover $\neg B$ must have caused the loop to end.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] As in the conditional rule, B must not have side effects.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] which is easily obtained by the assignment rule.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Finally, the postcondition $\{\neg x<10\wedge x\leq 10\}$ can be simplified to $\{x=10\}$ .
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] which follows from the skip rule and the consequence rule.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] In fact, the strange program is *partially* correct: if it happened to terminate, it is certain that x must have contained (by chance) the value of a's square root.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] In all other cases, it will not terminate; therefore, it is not *totally* correct.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] If the above ordinary while rule is replaced by the following one, the Hoare calculus can also be used to prove total correctness, i.e., termination as well as partial correctness.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Commonly, square brackets are used here instead of curly braces to indicate the different notion of program correctness.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] In this rule, in addition to maintaining the loop invariant, one also proves termination by way of an expression t, called the loop variant, whose value strictly decreases with respect to a well-founded relation < on some domain set D during each iteration.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Since < is well-founded, a strictly decreasing chain of members of D can have only finite length, so t cannot keep decreasing forever.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Given the loop invariant P, the condition B must imply that t is not a minimal element of D, for otherwise the body S could not decrease t any further, i.e. the premise of the rule would be false.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] the while rule for total correctness can be applied with e.g.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] Informally speaking, we have to prove that the distance $10-x$ decreases in every loop cycle, while it always remains non-negative; this process can go on only for a finite number of cycles.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/hoare-logic] For the second example of the previous section, of course, no expression t can be found that is decreased by the empty loop body, hence termination cannot be proved.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] In mathematics, an **invariant** is a property of a mathematical object (or a class of mathematical objects) which remains unchanged after operations or transformations of a certain type are applied to the objects.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The particular class of objects and type of transformations are usually indicated by the context in which the term is used.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] For example, the area of a triangle is an invariant with respect to isometries of the Euclidean plane.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The phrases "invariant under" and "invariant to" a transformation are both used.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] More generally, an invariant with respect to an equivalence relation is a property that is constant on each equivalence class.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Invariants are used in diverse areas of mathematics such as geometry, topology, algebra and discrete mathematics.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Some important classes of transformations are defined by an invariant they leave unchanged.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] For example, conformal maps are defined as transformations of the plane that preserve angles.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The discovery of invariants is an important step in the process of classifying mathematical objects.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] A simple example of invariance is expressed in our ability to count.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] For a finite set of objects of any kind, there is a number to which we always arrive, regardless of the order in which we count the objects in the set.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The quantity—a cardinal number—is associated with the set, and is invariant under the process of counting.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] An identity is an equation that remains true for all values of its variables.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] There are also inequalities that remain true when the values of their variables change.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The distance between two points on a number line is not changed by adding the same quantity to both numbers.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] On the other hand, multiplication does not have this same property, as distance is not invariant under multiplication.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Angles and ratios of distances are invariant under scalings, rotations, translations and reflections.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] These transformations produce similar shapes, which are the basis of trigonometry.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] In contrast, angles and ratios are not invariant under non-uniform scaling (such as stretching).
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The sum of a triangle's interior angles (180°) is invariant under all the above operations.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] As another example, all circles are similar: they can be transformed into each other, and the ratio of the circumference to the diameter is invariant (denoted by the Greek letter π (pi)).
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The MU puzzle is a good example of a logical problem where determining an invariant is of use for an impossibility proof.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] In light of this, one might wonder whether it is possible to convert MI into MU, using only these four transformation rules.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] One could spend many hours applying these transformation rules to strings.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] However, it might be quicker to find a property that is invariant to all rules (that is, not changed by any of them), and that demonstrates that getting to MU is impossible.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] By looking at the puzzle from a logical standpoint, one might realize that the only way to get rid of any I's is to have three consecutive I's in the string.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] This is an invariant to the problem, if for each of the transformation rules the following holds: if the invariant held before applying the rule, it will also hold after applying it.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The table above shows clearly that the invariant holds for each of the possible transformation rules, which means that whichever rule one picks, at whatever state, if the number of I's was not a multiple of three before applying the rule, then it will not be afterwards either.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Given that there is a single I in the starting string MI, and one is not a multiple of three, one can then conclude that it is impossible to go from MI to MU (as the number of I's will never be a multiple of three).
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] A subset *S* of the domain *U* of a mapping *T*: *U* → *U* is an **invariant set** under the mapping when $x\in S\iff T(x)\in S.$ The elements of *S* are not necessarily fixed, even though the set *S* is fixed in the power set of *U*.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] (Some authors use the terminology *setwise invariant,* vs.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] *pointwise invariant,* to distinguish between these cases.) For example, a circle is an invariant subset of the plane under a rotation about the circle's center.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Further, a conical surface is invariant as a set under a homothety of space.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] An invariant set of an operation *T* is also said to be **stable under** *T*.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] For example, the normal subgroups that are so important in group theory are those subgroups that are stable under the inner automorphisms of the ambient group.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] In linear algebra, if a linear transformation *T* has an eigenvector **v**, then the line through **0** and **v** is an invariant set under *T*, in which case the eigenvectors span an invariant subspace which is stable under *T*.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] When *T* is a screw displacement, the screw axis is an invariant line, though if the pitch is non-zero, *T* has no fixed points.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] In probability theory and ergodic theory, invariant sets are usually defined via the stronger property $x\in S\Leftrightarrow T(x)\in S.$ When the map T is measurable, invariant sets form a sigma-algebra, the invariant sigma-algebra.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The notion of invariance is formalized in three different ways in mathematics: via group actions, presentations, and deformation.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Firstly, if one has a group *G* acting on a mathematical object (or set of objects) *X,* then one may ask which points *x* are unchanged, "invariant" under the group action, or under an element *g* of the group.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Frequently, one will have a group acting on a set *X*, which leaves one to determine which objects in an *associated* set *F*(*X*) are invariant.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] For example, rotation in the plane about a point leaves the point about which it rotates invariant, while translation in the plane does not leave any points invariant, but does leave all lines parallel to the direction of translation invariant as lines.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Formally, define the set of lines in the plane *P* as *L*(*P*); then a rigid motion of the plane takes lines to lines – the group of rigid motions acts on the set of lines – and one may ask which lines are unchanged by an action.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] More importantly, one may define a *function* on a set, such as "radius of a circle in the plane", and then ask if this function is invariant under a group action, such as rigid motions.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Dual to the notion of invariants are *coinvariants,* also known as *orbits,* which formalizes the notion of congruence: objects that can be taken to each other by a group action.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] For example, under the group of rigid motions of the plane, the perimeter of a triangle is an invariant, while the set of triangles congruent to a given triangle is a coinvariant.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] These are connected as follows: invariants are constant on coinvariants (for example, congruent triangles have the same perimeter), while two objects that agree in the value of one invariant may or may not be congruent (for example, two triangles with the same perimeter need not be congruent).
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] In classification problems, one might seek to find a complete set of invariants, such that if two objects have the same values for this set of invariants, then they are congruent.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] For example, triangles such that all three sides are equal are congruent under rigid motions, via SSS congruence, and thus the lengths of all three sides form a complete set of invariants for triangles.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The three angle measures of a triangle are also invariant under rigid motions, but do not form a complete set as incongruent triangles can share the same angle measures.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] However, if one allows scaling in addition to rigid motions, then the AAA similarity criterion shows that this is a complete set of invariants.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Secondly, a function may be defined in terms of some presentation or decomposition of a mathematical object; for instance, the Euler characteristic of a cell complex is defined as the alternating sum of the number of cells in each dimension.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] This is the case for the Euler characteristic, and a general method for defining and computing invariants is to define them for a given presentation, and then show that they are independent of the choice of presentation.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Note that there is no notion of a group action in this sense.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Thirdly, if one is studying an object that varies in a family, as is common in algebraic geometry and differential geometry, one may ask if the property is unchanged under perturbation (for example, if an object is constant on families or invariant under change of metric).
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] In computer science, an invariant is a logical assertion that is always held to be true during a certain phase of execution of a computer program.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] For example, a loop invariant is a condition that is true at the beginning and the end of every iteration of a loop.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Invariants are especially useful when reasoning about the correctness of a computer program.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The theory of optimizing compilers, the methodology of design by contract, and formal methods for determining program correctness, all rely heavily on invariants.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Programmers often use assertions in their code to make invariants explicit.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Some object oriented programming languages have a special syntax for specifying class invariants.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Abstract interpretation tools can compute simple invariants of given imperative computer programs.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] The kinds of properties that can be found depend on the abstract domains used.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Typical example properties are single integer variable ranges like `0<=x<1024`, relations between several variables like `0<=i-j<2*n-1`, and modulus information like `y%4==0`.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] Academic research prototypes also consider simple properties of pointer structures.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] More sophisticated invariants generally have to be provided manually.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] In particular, when verifying an imperative program using Hoare logic, a loop invariant has to be provided manually for each loop in the program, which is one of the reasons that this approach is generally impractical for most programs.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] In the context of the above MU puzzle example, there is currently no general automated tool that can detect that a derivation from MI to MU is impossible using only the rules 1–4.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/invariant-mathematics] However, once the abstraction from the string to the number of its "I"s has been made by hand, leading, for example, to the following C program, an abstract interpretation tool will be able to detect that `ICount%3` cannot be 0, and hence the "while"-loop will never terminate.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] In computer programming, a **postcondition** is a condition or predicate that must always be true just after the execution of some section of code or after an operation in a formal specification.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] Postconditions are sometimes tested using assertions within the code itself.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] Often, postconditions are simply included in the documentation of the affected section of code.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] For example: The result of a factorial is always an integer and greater than or equal to 1.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] So a program that calculates the factorial of an input number would have postconditions that the result after the calculation be an integer and that it be greater than or equal to 1.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] Another example: a program that calculates the square root of an input number might have the postconditions that the result be a number and that its square be equal to the input.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] In some software design approaches, postconditions, along with preconditions and class invariants, are components of the software construction method design by contract.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] The postcondition for any routine is a declaration of the properties which are guaranteed upon completion of the routine's execution.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] As it relates to the routine's contract, the postcondition offers assurance to potential callers that in cases in which the routine is called in a state in which its precondition holds, the properties declared by the postcondition are assured.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] The following example written in Eiffel sets the value of a class attribute `hour` based on a caller-provided argument `a_hour`.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] The postcondition follows the keyword `ensure`.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] In this example, the postcondition guarantees, in cases in which the precondition holds (i.e., when `a_hour` represents a valid hour of the day), that after the execution of `set_hour`, the class attribute `hour` will have the same value as `a_hour`.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] The tag `hour_set` describes this postcondition clause and serves to identify it in case of a runtime postcondition violation.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] In the presence of inheritance, the routines inherited by descendant classes (subclasses) do so with their contracts, that is their preconditions and postconditions, in force.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] This means that any implementations or redefinitions of inherited routines also have to be written to comply with their inherited contracts.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] Postconditions can be modified in redefined routines, but they may only be strengthened.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/postcondition] That is, the redefined routine may increase the benefits it provides to the client, but may not decrease those benefits.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] In computer programming, a **precondition** is a condition or predicate that must always be true just prior to the execution of some section of code or before an operation in a formal specification.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] If a precondition is violated, the effect of the section of code becomes undefined and thus may or may not carry out its intended work.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] Preconditions that are missing, insufficient, or not formally proved (or have an incorrect attempted proof), or are not checked statically or dynamically, can give rise to Security problems, particularly in unsafe languages that are not strongly typed.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] Often, preconditions are simply included in the documentation of the affected section of code.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] Preconditions are sometimes tested using guards or assertions within the code itself, and some languages have specific syntactic constructions for doing so.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] The factorial function is only defined where its parameter is an integer greater than or equal to zero.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] So an implementation of the factorial function would have a precondition that its parameter be an integer *and* that the parameter be greater than or equal to zero.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] Alternatively the type system of the language may be used to specify that the parameter of the factorial function is a natural number (unsigned integer), which can be formally verified automatically by a compiler's type checker.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] In addition where numeric types have a limited range (as they do in most programming languages) the precondition must also specify the maximum value that the parameter may have if overflow is not to occur.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] (e.g. if an implementation of factorial returns the result in a 64-bit unsigned integer then the parameter must be less than 21 because factorial(21) is larger than the maximum unsigned integer that can be stored in 64 bits).
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] Where the language supports range sub-types (e.g.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] Ada) such constraints can be automatically verified by the type system.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] More complex constraints can be formally verified interactively with a proof assistant.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] Preconditions in object-oriented software development are an essential part of design by contract.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] Design by contract also includes notions of postcondition and class invariant.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] The precondition for any routine defines any constraints on object state which are necessary for successful execution.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] From the program developer's viewpoint, this constitutes the routine caller's portion of the contract.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] The caller then is obliged to ensure that the precondition holds prior to calling the routine.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] The reward for the caller's effort is expressed in the called routine's postcondition.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] The routine in the following example written in Eiffel takes as an argument an integer which must be a valid value for an hour of the day, i. e., 0 through 23, inclusively.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] The precondition follows the keyword `require`.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] It specifies that the argument must be greater than or equal to zero and less than 24.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] The tag `valid_argument` describes this precondition clause and serves to identify it in case of a runtime precondition violation.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] In the presence of inheritance, the routines inherited by descendant classes (subclasses) do so with their preconditions in force.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] This means that any implementations or redefinitions of inherited routines also have to be written to comply with their inherited contract.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] Preconditions can be modified in redefined routines, but they may only be weakened.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/precondition] That is, the redefined routine may lessen the obligation of the client, but not increase it.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] In computer science, **termination analysis** is program analysis which attempts to determine whether the evaluation of a given program halts for *each* input.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] This means to determine whether the input program computes a *total* function.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] It is closely related to the halting problem, which is to determine whether a given program halts for a *given* input and which is undecidable.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] A *termination proof* is a type of mathematical proof that plays a critical role in formal verification because total correctness of an algorithm depends on termination.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] A simple, general method for constructing termination proofs involves associating a **measure** with each step of an algorithm.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] The measure is taken from the domain of a well-founded relation, such as from the ordinal numbers.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] If the measure "decreases" according to the relation along every possible step of the algorithm, it must terminate, because there are no infinite descending chains with respect to a well-founded relation.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Some types of termination analysis can automatically generate or imply the existence of a termination proof.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] An example of a programming language construct which may or may not terminate is a loop, as they can be run repeatedly.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] If the value of *SIZE_OF_DATA* is non-negative, fixed and finite, the loop will eventually terminate, assuming *process_data* terminates too.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Some loops can be shown to always terminate or never terminate through human inspection.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] For example, the following loop will, in theory, never stop.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] However, it may halt when executed on a physical machine due to arithmetic overflow: either leading to an exception or causing the counter to wrap to a negative value and enabling the loop condition to be fulfilled.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] In termination analysis one may also try to determine the termination behaviour of some program depending on some unknown input.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] The following example illustrates this problem.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Here the loop condition is defined using some value UNKNOWN, where the value of UNKNOWN is not known (e.g. defined by the user's input when the program is executed).
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Here the termination analysis must take into account all possible values of UNKNOWN and find out that in the possible case of UNKNOWN = 0 (as in the original example) the termination cannot be shown.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] There is, however, no general procedure for determining whether an expression involving looping instructions will halt, even when humans are tasked with the inspection.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] The theoretical reason for this is the undecidability of the halting problem: there cannot exist some algorithm which determines whether any given program stops after finitely many computation steps.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] In practice one fails to show termination (or non-termination) because every algorithm works with a finite set of methods being able to extract relevant information out of a given program.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] But because each method is only able to "see" some specific reasons for (non)termination, even through combination of such methods one cannot cover all possible reasons for (non)termination.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Recursive functions and loops are equivalent in expression; any expression involving loops can be written using recursion, and vice versa.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Thus the termination of recursive expressions is also undecidable in general.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Most recursive expressions found in common usage (i.e. not pathological) can be shown to terminate through various means, usually depending on the definition of the expression itself.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] As an example, the function argument in the recursive expression for the factorial function below will always decrease by 1; by the well-ordering property of natural numbers, the argument will eventually reach 1 and the recursion will terminate.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Termination check is very important in dependently typed programming language and theorem proving systems like Rocq and Agda.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] These systems use Curry-Howard isomorphism between programs and proofs.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Proofs over inductively defined data types were traditionally described using induction principles.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] However, it was found later that describing a program via a recursively defined function with pattern matching is a more natural way of proving than using induction principles directly.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Unfortunately, allowing non-terminating definitions leads to logical inconsistency in type theories, which is why Agda and Rocq have termination checkers built-in.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] One of the approaches to termination checking in dependently typed programming languages are sized types.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] The main idea is to annotate the types over which we can recurse with size annotations and allow recursive calls only on smaller arguments.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Sized types are implemented in Agda as a syntactic extension.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] There are several research teams that work on new methods that can show (non)termination.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] Many researchers include these methods into programs that try to analyze the termination behavior automatically (so without human interaction).
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] An ongoing aspect of research is to allow the existing methods to be used to analyze termination behavior of programs written in "real world" programming languages.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] For declarative languages like Haskell, Mercury and Prolog, many results exist (mainly because of the strong mathematical background of these languages).
[src:hoare-logic-deep/termination-analysis] The research community also works on new methods to analyze termination behavior of programs written in imperative languages like C and Java.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] More formally, a relation is well-founded if: $(\forall S\subseteq X)\;[S\neq \varnothing \implies (\exists m\in S)(\forall s\in S)\lnot (s\mathrel {R} m)].$ Some authors include an extra condition that R is set-like, i.e., that the elements less than any given element form a set.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] Equivalently, assuming the axiom of dependent choice, a relation is well-founded when it contains no infinite descending chains, meaning there is no infinite sequence *x*0, *x*1, *x*2, ... of elements of X such that *x**n*+1 *R* *x**n* for every natural number n.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] In order theory, a partial order is called well-founded if the corresponding strict order is a well-founded relation.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] If the order is a total order, then it is called a well-order.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] In set theory, a set x is called a **well-founded set** if the set membership relation is well-founded on the transitive closure of x.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] The axiom of regularity, which is one of the axioms of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory, asserts that all sets are well-founded.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] A relation R is **converse well-founded**, **upwards well-founded**, or **Noetherian** on X, if the converse relation *R*−1 is well-founded on X.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] In this case R is also said to satisfy the ascending chain condition.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] In the context of rewriting systems, a Noetherian relation is also called **terminating**.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] Well-founded induction is sometimes called Noetherian induction, after Emmy Noether.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] On par with induction, well-founded relations also support construction of objects by transfinite recursion.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] Let (*X*, *R*) be a set-like well-founded relation and F a function that assigns an object *F*(*x*, *g*) to each pair of an element *x* ∈ *X* and a function g on the set {*y*: *y* *R* *x*} of predecessors of x.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] That is, if we want to construct a function G on X, we may define *G*(*x*) using the values of *G*(*y*) for *y* *R* *x*.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] As an example, consider the well-founded relation (**N**, *S*), where **N** is the set of all natural numbers, and S is the graph of the successor function *x* ↦ *x*+1.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] Then induction on S is the usual mathematical induction, and recursion on S gives primitive recursion.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] If we consider the order relation (**N**, <), we obtain complete induction, and course-of-values recursion.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] The statement that (**N**, <) is well-founded is also known as the well-ordering principle.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] There are other interesting special cases of well-founded induction.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] When the well-founded relation is the usual ordering on the class of all ordinal numbers, the technique is called transfinite induction.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] When the well-founded set is a set of recursively defined data structures, the technique is called structural induction.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] When the well-founded relation is set membership on the universal class, the technique is known as ∈-induction.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] If (*X*, <) is a well-founded relation and x is an element of X, then the descending chains starting at x are all finite, but this does not mean that their lengths are necessarily bounded.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] Consider the following example: Let X be the union of the positive integers with a new element ω that is bigger than any integer.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] Then X is a well-founded set, but there are descending chains starting at ω of arbitrary great (finite) length; the chain ω, *n* − 1, *n* − 2, ..., 2, 1 has length n for any n.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] The Mostowski collapse lemma implies that set membership is a universal among the extensional well-founded relations: for any set-like well-founded relation R on a class X that is extensional, there exists a class C such that (*X*, *R*) is isomorphic to (*C*, ∈).
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] A relation R is said to be reflexive if *a* *R* *a* holds for every a in the domain of the relation.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] Every reflexive relation on a nonempty domain has infinite descending chains, because any constant sequence is a descending chain.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] For example, in the natural numbers with their usual order ≤, we have 1 ≥ 1 ≥ 1 ≥ ....
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] To avoid these trivial descending sequences, when working with a partial order ≤, it is common to apply the definition of well foundedness (perhaps implicitly) to the alternate relation < defined such that *a* < *b* if and only if *a* ≤ *b* and *a* ≠ *b*.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] More generally, when working with a preorder ≤, it is common to use the relation < defined such that *a* < *b* if and only if *a* ≤ *b* and *b* ≰ *a*.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] In the context of the natural numbers, this means that the relation <, which is well-founded, is used instead of the relation ≤, which is not.
[src:hoare-logic-deep/well-founded-relation] In some texts, the definition of a well-founded relation is changed from the definition above to include these conventions.
